# Interrupt Handling Standards (Embedded)

This document defines standards for ISR design, deferred work patterns, priority assignment, and shared state protection in embedded firmware.

---

## Core Principle: ISRs Must Be Short, Safe, and Predictable

An interrupt service routine must complete in bounded time, perform no blocking operations, and communicate with the main application through lock-free mechanisms only.

---

## ISR Duration Budget

| Category | Max Duration | Rationale |
|----------|-------------|-----------|
| Fast ISR (DMA complete, GPIO) | < 1 us | Minimize blocking of lower-priority IRQs |
| Medium ISR (UART byte, SPI) | < 5 us | Acceptable for most systems |
| Complex ISR (protocol decode) | < 10 us | Only if no higher-priority ISR exists |
| **Hard limit** | < 50 us | Any ISR exceeding this must be redesigned |

If processing requires more time, defer to a task (see Deferred Work Patterns below).

---

## ISR Rules

### Mandatory

- [ ] No heap allocation (`malloc`, `free`, `new`) in ISR
- [ ] No blocking calls (`sleep`, `mutex_lock`, `semaphore_wait`) in ISR
- [ ] No `printf` or formatted string output in ISR
- [ ] No floating-point arithmetic in ISR (unless FPU lazy stacking is enabled and understood)
- [ ] All ISR code paths have bounded execution time
- [ ] ISR clears the interrupt source before returning
- [ ] Shared variables accessed in ISR are declared `volatile`

### Recommended

- [ ] ISR sets a flag or enqueues data, then returns
- [ ] Heavy processing done in task context via deferred work
- [ ] ISR entry/exit timing instrumented (GPIO toggle or DWT cycle counter)
- [ ] ISR count/rate monitored for anomaly detection

---

## Deferred Work Patterns

### Pattern 1: Flag and Poll

Simplest pattern for low-frequency events.

```c
static volatile bool data_ready = false;

void UART_IRQHandler(void) {
    uart_read_byte_into_buffer();
    data_ready = true;
    clear_irq_pending();
}

void main_loop(void) {
    while (1) {
        if (data_ready) {
            data_ready = false;
            process_uart_data();
        }
        enter_sleep();
    }
}
```

### Pattern 2: Queue (ISR to Task)

For high-frequency events or RTOS-based systems.

```c
static ring_buf_t sensor_queue;

void ADC_IRQHandler(void) {
    uint16_t sample = ADC->DR;
    ring_put(&sensor_queue, sample);
    clear_irq_pending();
}

void sensor_task(void *arg) {
    uint16_t sample;
    while (1) {
        if (ring_get(&sensor_queue, &sample)) {
            process_sample(sample);
        } else {
            os_task_yield();
        }
    }
}
```

### Pattern 3: Semaphore Signal (RTOS)

For waking a blocked task from ISR.

```c
void DMA_Complete_IRQHandler(void) {
    clear_dma_irq();
    os_semaphore_give_from_isr(&dma_sem);
}

void transfer_task(void *arg) {
    while (1) {
        os_semaphore_take(&dma_sem, OS_WAIT_FOREVER);
        process_dma_buffer();
    }
}
```

### Pattern Selection Guide

| Event Rate | Latency Requirement | Pattern | RTOS Required? |
|-----------|---------------------|---------|----------------|
| < 10 Hz | Soft (ms) | Flag and poll | No |
| 10-1000 Hz | Medium (100 us) | Queue | No |
| > 1 kHz | Hard (< 100 us) | Direct ISR processing | No |
| Any | Wake blocked task | Semaphore signal | Yes |

